Here's an example of how to automatically generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document using the `tocbasic` and `tocbibind` packages. In this example, I'll show how to create a simple document with a table of contents that is updated as you add new sections.

First, you need to install the required packages:
```bash
\usepackage{tocbasic}
\usepackage{tocbibind}
```
Then, create your document and add the sections you want to include in the table of contents. In this example, I'll create three sections: Introduction, Methodology, and Results.
```latex
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{tocbasic}
\usepackage{tocbibind}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Vivamus at magna vitae eros bibendum mollis vel in enim. Vestibulum ante ipsum primis in faucibus orci luctus et ultrices posuere cubilia Curae; Donec tincidunt magna quis tellus blandit, sit amet blandit nulla rhoncus.

\section{Methodology}
Sed posuere consectetur est at lobortis. Donec ullamcorper, libero sed faucibus interdum, velit velit malesuada tellus, eu bibendum purus nisl in lectus. Suspendisse auctor, ipsum a convallis vehicula, dui velit lacinia justo, sed tincidunt nulla leo non velit.

\section{Results}
Donec vehicula, elit ac aliquam viverra, lectus risus tincidunt velit, vitae viverra ipsum ligula eu massa. Donec sagittis pharetra purus, non varius massa porttitor vel. Donec tincidunt, nulla non fermentum vestibulum, sapien velit pulvinar nisi, vel posuere lectus massa in nulla.

\end{document}
```
When you run this example, you'll see a table of contents with the sections you've added:

Table of Contents

I. Introduction
II. Methodology
III. Results

You can further customize the table of contents by using additional commands, such as changing the section titles' font size or style, adding page numbers, or adjusting the spacing between the sections. For more information, refer to the `tocbasic` and `tocbibind` package documentation.

To create a chessboard diagram in LaTeX, you can use the `chessboard` package. First, you need to install it using the following command in the terminal or command prompt:
```
\usepackage{chessboard}
```
Then, you can use the following code to create the diagram:
```sql
\setchessboard{stripes={1}{0.5}}
\chessboard{8}{8}
```
This code will create a chessboard diagram with alternating light and dark squares, and the board size is 8x8. If you want a different board size, simply change the numbers in the `chessboard` command.

Here's the complete code:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\setchessboard{stripes={1}{0.5}}
\chessboard{8}{8}

\end{document}
```
This will produce a chessboard diagram in your LaTeX document. If you want to include the diagram in a figure environment, you can use the following code:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\setchessboard{stripes={1}{0.5}}
\chessboard{8}{8}
\caption{Chessboard diagram}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```
This will include the chessboard diagram as a figure in your LaTeX document.

